+/*
+ * openttdoom speed fork: per-train pathfinder DECISION CACHE.
+ *
+ * Motivation: the reader/clock trains of the logic machine follow a FIXED track,
+ * so at every choice point the YAPF A* search recomputes the same answer. The
+ * track a train takes out of a junction is a pure function of (where its current
+ * reservation ends, its destination, the static rail layout); it does NOT depend
+ * on other trains' dynamic reservations (those only affect whether the reservation
+ * SUCCEEDS, handled separately by ExtendTrainReservation before YAPF runs).
+ *
+ * So we memoise the YAPF track choice per train, keyed on the exact pathfinding
+ * inputs. The cache is consulted at the DoTrainPathfind boundary in ChooseTrainTrack.
+ *
+ * SAFETY (this must never change where a train goes):
+ *   - Gated entirely by _ottdoom_logic_map. Flag off == exact stock behaviour, the
+ *     cache code is never entered.
+ *   - The cache only ever supplies the FIRST trackdir to follow. It NEVER replaces
+ *     the reservation: on a hit we still call the real YAPF to perform the path
+ *     reservation. The only thing reused is the cheap branch where YAPF is asked
+ *     to choose but NOT reserve (reserve_track == false): there the result has no
+ *     side effects, so reusing it is provably a no-op-equivalent.
+ *   - The key includes the global rail-layout change counter
+ *     (CSegmentCostCacheBase::s_rail_change_counter), the train's destination tile
+ *     and current order index, and all the geometric inputs, so any track edit,
+ *     signal change, order change or destination change misses the cache and
+ *     re-runs YAPF.
+ *   - The cache is process-local (keyed by VehicleID), NOT stored in the savegame,
+ *     so it adds zero bytes to any save and cannot affect a deterministic re-run's
+ *     output.
+ *
+ * Because a correct skip of the reserving A* would require replaying YAPF's full
+ * node path (desync-risky surgery), this cache deliberately only short-circuits the
